06494nam a22009855i 9780228009733DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a2021386541  a97802280097337 a10.1515/97802280097332doi  a(DE-B1597)655439  a(OCoLC)1251927267  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA00aBL625.7b.R476 2021 4aBL625.7b.R476 2021 7aREL0840002bisacsh04a200.82097122300aRelation and Resistance :bRacialized Women, Religion, and Diaspora /ced. by Becky R. Lee, Sailaja Krishnamurti. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAdvancing Studies in Religion ;v1000tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tNavigating Religion, Nation, and Identity -- tGrounded Religiosities -- tWriting Home -- tThe Role of Women in the Pre-Second World War Japanese Diaspora in Canada -- tDiasporic Sikh Women -- tWomen in Transnational Religious Communities -- tDiaspora as a Spectrum -- tChinese Buddhist Nuns in Canada -- tSyrian Malabar Christian Diaspora in Canada -- tMuslim Model Minorities and the Politics of Diasporic Piety -- tBuilding Relations, Imagining Futures -- tBrown Girl in the Ring -- tTowards a Canadian Islam -- tDiaspora, Spirituality, Kinship, and Nationhood -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Canada, women’s bodies are often at the centre of debates about religious pluralism, multiculturalism, and secularism. Women have long played a critical role in building and maintaining diasporic religious communities and networks, and they have also been catalysts for change and transformation within religious groups and the wider community.Relation and Resistance explores the stories and lives of racialized women connected with religious diaspora communities in Canada. Contributors from across disciplines show how women are conceptualizing traditions in transformative ways, challenging prevailing assumptions about diasporic religion as nostalgically entrenched in the past. The collected essays include chapters on feminist and queer women thinking critically about Hindu and Muslim identities and beliefs and challenging anti-Black racism and settler colonialism; Afro-Caribbean and Métis writers using literature to explore religion and belonging; the impact of women’s participation in Japanese, Chinese, and Pakistani transnational religious organizations; and marriage, migration, and gender equality in the Punjabi Sikh and Malayali Christian communities. The volume closes with a chapter exploring Métis diasporic experience and inviting readers to think critically about diasporic religion on Indigenous land.An innovative and timely volume, Relation and Resistance reveals that a deeper understanding of women’s experiences of displacement, migration, race, and gender is critical to the study of religion in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminismzCanada. 0aMinority womenxReligious lifezCanada. 0aWomen and religionzCanada. 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh  aBuddhism.  aCanada.  aChristianity.  aHinduism.  aIslam.  aSikhism.  acolonialism.  aconservatism.  adisplacement.  afaith communities.  afeminism.  agender.  aimmigration.  aindigenous.  amarriage.  amigration.  amulticulturalism.  areligiosity.  areligious transformation.  atransnational.  awomens organizations.1 aBerns-McGown, Rima, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Andrea A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDerry, K